{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-46-27-165Z","slug":"honest-priorities","locale":"de","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:46:35.083Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2024-10-23--honest-priorities/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2024-10-23--honest-priorities/de/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/honest-priorities/de/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-46-27-165Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"da1f34ee6d26d02e8809471cbcff241d7299d39dd7c226e4c02b3cc242fa29bb","outputHash":"797274bb216e190332604f984a817c49294c6986e130896616de9f6891fb602b","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that using a static, multiple‑choice “Priority” dropdown (e.g., P1‑P4) in issue trackers quickly becomes a “priority inflation” trap, as teams keep adding higher levels (P0, P00, etc.) to accommodate new urgent work. It explains why a single numeric or categorical field cannot capture the fluid, multidimensional nature of real‑world priority, and warns that unchecked growth leads to bloated backlogs, “z‑index”‑style wars, and eventual technical limits. The author suggests alternatives such as a neutral numeric baseline, composite scoring, or established frameworks like MoSCoW and the Kano model, and recommends regular archiving of stale tickets. The tone is a mix of informal rant and practical analysis, aimed at engineering managers, product owners, and Jira administrators who design backlog‑triage processes.","totalInputTokens":7208,"totalOutputTokens":1828,"totalCacheReadTokens":1280,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":6250,"totalCostUsd":0.000610152,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":7,"totalInputTokens":7208,"totalOutputTokens":1828,"totalCacheReadTokens":1280,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":62